equation} \par Because $x$ is large, we perform the change of variables $u = \sqrt{x \frac{|f''(0.455137201554065)|}{2}}(t-0.455137201554065)$, rewriting the integral as \begin{equation} g(0.455137201554065) e^{- x f(0.455137201554065)} \int_{\sqrt{x \frac{|f''(0.455137201554065)|}{2}} (a-0.455137201554065)}^{\sqrt{x \frac{|f''(0.455137201554065)|}{2}} (b-0.455137201554065)} \sqrt{\frac{2}{x |f''(0.455137201554065)|}} e^{-u^2} \, dt \end{equation} \par Since $x \to \infty$, we approximate this as \begin{equation} g(0.455137201554065) e^{- x f(0.455137201554065)} \sqrt{\frac{2}{x |f''(0.455137201554065)|} } \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-u^2} \, dt \end{equation} \par Solving the integral and evaluating, we find that \par \begin{equation} \boxed{I(x) \approx 0.719832722044118 \sqrt{\pi} \sqrt{\frac{1}{x}} e^{0.157699686244314 x}} \end{equation}

Example question: Consider the integral \par \begin{equation} I(x) = \int_{-0.6}^{0.9} (0.6 t^{5} + 1.8 t) e^{+ x (2.3 t^{4} + 2.0 \sin{\left(t \right)} - 2.6)} \, dt \end{equation} \par Develop an analytical formula for $I(x)$ that is accurate as $x \to \infty$.
Example solution: The integral is of the form \begin{equation} I(x) = \int_{a}^{b} g(t) e^{+ x f(t)} \, dt \end{equation} \par where $a=-0.6$, $b=0.9$, $g(t) = 0.6 t^{5} + 1.8 t$, and $f(t) = 2.3 t^{4} + 2.0 \sin{\left(t \right)} - 2.6$. This means we can use Laplace's method to develop an analytical approximation in the limit that $x \to \infty$. \par In this limit, the integral will be dominated by the integrand near the maximum of $f(t)$ within the bounds $[-0.6, 0.9]$. So, to simplify the integral, we will expand the integrand around this maximum. \par However, it is impossible to compute the maximum of $f(t)$ on the bounds analytically. We must approximate it numerically. We will use the a few iterations of the dual annealing algorithm to achieve this. Using a few iterations of dual annealing, we find that the maximum of $f(t)$ occurs at $t_0 = [0.9]$. \par Since the integral is dominated by the value of the integrand near b, we Taylor expand the integrand around this point. \begin{equation} I(x) =  \int_{a}^{b} (g(b) + (t-b)g'(b)+...) e^{+ x (f(b) + (t-b) f'(b) + ...)} \, dt \end{equation} We can then approximate \begin{equation} I(x) \approx \int_{a}^{b} g(b) e^{+ x (f(b) + (t-b) f'(b))} \, dt \end{equation} Pulling out the constant in the integral gives \begin{equation} I(x) \approx g(b) e^{+ x f(b)} \int_{a}^{b} e^{+ x (t-b) f'(b)}  \, dt \end{equation} \par Since $x$ is large, we perform the change of variables $u = x (t-b) |f'(b)|$, rewriting the integral as \begin{equation} I(x) \approx g(b) e^{+ x f(b)} \int_{x (a-b) |f'(b)|}^{0} \frac{1}{x |f'(b)|} e^{u} \, dt \end{equation} Since $x \to \infty$, we approximate this with new bounds as \begin{equation} I(x) \approx g(b) e^{+ x f(b)} \frac{1}{x |f'(b)|} \int_{-\infty}^{0} e^{u} \, dt \end{equation} \par Solving the integral and evaluating, we find that \par \begin{equation} \boxed{I(x) \approx \frac{0.248338245156517 e^{0.475683819254967 x}}{x}} \end{equation}


