Assuming we have found the maximum point $t_0$ within the interval, we can Taylor expand the integrand around this point:

\begin{equation}
I(x) = \int_{-0.9}^{-0.3} (-2.0 t^{4}) e^{-x(-2.8\sin(t)+0.1\operatorname{atan}(t)+0.7)} \, dt \approx (-2.0 t_0^4)e^{-x(-2.8\sin(t_0)+0.1\operatorname{atan}(t_0)+0.7)}\int_{-0.9}^{-0.3} e^{x(-2.8(t-t_0)\cos(t_0)+0.1(t-t_0)\frac{1}{t_0}+\cdots)} \, dt
\end{equation}

Since $x$ is large, we perform the change of variables $u = x (-2.8 (t - t_0) \cos(t_0) + 0.1 (t - t_0) \frac{1}{t_0})$, rewriting the integral as:

\begin{equation}
I(x) \approx (-2.0 t_0^4)e^{-x(-2.8\sin(t_0)+0.1\operatorname{atan}(t_0)+0.7)}\int_{-x(-0.9-t_0)\cos(t_0)}^{x(-0.3-t_0)\cos(t_0)} \frac{1}{x (-2.8 (t - t_0) \cos(t_0) + 0.1 (t - t_0) \frac{1}{t_0})} e^{u} \, du
\end{equation}

Since $x \to \infty$, we approximate this with new bounds as:

\begin{equation}
I(x) \approx (-2.0 t_0^4)e^{-x(-2.8\sin(t_0)+0.1\operatorname{atan}(t_0)+0.7)}\frac{1}{x}\int_{-\infty}^{0} e^{u} \, du
