Let's assume that we have found the maximum point $t_0$ within the given interval. Then, we Taylor expand the integrand around this point:

\begin{equation}
I(x) = \int_{0.4}^{0.6} (g(t_0) + (t-t_0)g'(t_0)+...) e^{- x (f(t_0) + (t-t_0) f'(t_0) + ...)} \, dt
\end{equation}

We can then approximate:

\begin{equation}
I(x) \approx g(t_0) e^{- x f(t_0)} \int_{0.4}^{0.6} e^{- x (t-t_0) f'(t_0)} \, dt
\end{equation}

Since $x$ is large, we perform the change of variables $u = - x (t-t_0) |f'(t_0)|$, rewriting the integral as:

\begin{equation}
I(x) \approx g(t_0) e^{- x f(t_0)} \frac{1}{|f'(t_0)|} \int_{x (t_0 - 0.6) |f'(t_0)|}^{x (t_0 - 0.4) |f'(t_0)|} e^{u} \, dt
\end{equation}

Since $x \to \infty$, we approximate this with new bounds as:

\begin{equation}
I(x) \approx g(t_0) e^{- x f(t_0)} \frac{1}{|f'(t_0)|} \int_{-\infty}^{0} e^{u} \, dt
\end{equation}

Solving the integral and evaluating, we find that:

\begin{equation}
\boxed{I(x) \approx \frac{g(t_0) e^{- x f(t_0)}}{|f'(t_0)|}}
\end{equation}

To get a SymPy convertible formula, we can use the following expressions for $g(t)$ and $f(t)$:

\begin{equation}
g(t) = - 0.4 t^{5} + 0.4 t + 2.1 \sin{\left(t \right)}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
f(t) = - 2.3 t^{5} - 1.5 t^{3} + 1.7 \cos{\left(t \right)} - 2.5
\end{equation}

